image.latex-image:

\tikzset{%
}
\begin{tikzpicture}[auto, thick]
\pgfmathsetmacro{\rad}{3}
\pgfmathsetmacro{\angle}{65}

\coordinate (c1) at (0,0);
\draw [dotted] (c1) circle (\rad);
\draw [dotted] (c1) -- ($ (c1) + (\rad, 0) $);
\draw ($ (c1) + (\rad,0) $)
        arc (0:\angle:\rad) 
        node [above] {$(x,y)$}
        -- (c1);
\fill ($ (c1) + (\angle:\rad) $) circle [radius=2pt];
\draw ($ (c1) + (0:0.2*\rad) $) arc (0:\angle:0.2*\rad)
    node [pos=0.5, right] {$\theta$};

\coordinate (c2) at (\angle:\rad);
\coordinate (c2c) at (-\angle:\rad);
\coordinate (c3) at ($ (c2)!0.5!(c2c) $);
\draw (c1) -- (c2) node [pos=0.5, left] {1}
    -- (c3) node [pos=0.5, right] {$\sin \theta$}
    -- (c1) node [pos=0.5, below] {$\cos \theta$};
\end{tikzpicture}

statement.p:
If an angle \theta is put in standard position
and terminates at a point (x,y) on the unit circle,
then the trigonometric functions of \theta are defined
by

     \cos \theta &= x 
     \sin \theta &= y 
     \tan \theta &= \frac{\sin \theta}{\cos \theta} = \frac{y}{x} 
     \sec \theta &= \frac{1}{\cos \theta} = \frac{1}{x} 
     \cot \theta &= \frac{\cos \theta}{\sin \theta} = \frac{x}{y} 
     \csc \theta &= \frac{1}{\sin \theta} = \frac{1}{y}

ul.li:
Go half a right angle to \theta=\frac{\pi}{4} with a terminal point 
where x=y at (\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}},\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}).
Using the coordinates and slope of the terminal edge gives:
 \cos \frac{\pi}{4} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} 
    \qquad \sin \frac{\pi}{4} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} 
    \qquad \tan \frac{\pi}{4} = 1

